{{Met-stub}}

The [[Latin Songwriters Hall of Fame]] (LSHOF) was established in 2012 by [[Rudy Pérez]] and [[Desmond Child]] in the United States to "educate, preserve, honor and celebrate the legacy of the greatest [[Latin music (genre)|Latin]] songwriters from all over the world and their music in every genre".<ref name="miaminews">{{cite news|author1=S. Pajot|title=Latin Songwriters Hall of Fame Launches in Miami, Announces 2013 Nominees|url=http://blogs.miaminewtimes.com/crossfade/2012/12/latin_songwriters_hall_of_fame_2013_nominees.php|accessdate=October 30, 2014|work=[[Miami New Times]]|publisher=[[Voice Media Group]]|date=December 12, 2012}}</ref> According to Child, the organization was created to recognize songwriters who are rarely acknowledged for their compositions.<ref name="Puga">{{cite news|last1=Puga|first1=Kristina|title=Two Cuban-American music producing icons inaugurate the Latin Songwriters Hall of Fame|url=http://nbclatino.com/2013/04/21/two-cuban-american-music-producing-icons-inaugurate-the-latin-songwriters-hall-of-fame/|accessdate=December 23, 2017|work=NBC Latino|date=April 23, 2013}}</ref> He cited "[[Livin' la Vida Loca]]" by [[Ricky Martin]] as an example when searching the song's lyrics for the Internet with neither him nor [[Draco Rosa]] being credited for writing the song.<ref name="Levin">{{cite news|last1=Levin|first1=Jordan|title=Latin songwriters to be honored in Miami Beach|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/entertainment/ent-columns-blogs/jordan-levin/article39058881.html|work=Miami Herald|date=April 21, 2013}}</ref>
The organization's committee is made up of music professional from 21 Spanish- and Portuguese-speaking countries in Latin America, Europe, and the United States. Nominees for the LSHOF are chosen by the committees while inductees are voted by the public.<ref name="Levin"/> For a songwriter to be considered, they must have a composed a [[hit song]] at least twenty years old.<ref name="Puga"/> Both living and deceased songwriters are eligible to be inducted into the LSHOF.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://www.latinsonghall.com/about-us/|website=Latin Songwriters Hall of Fame|accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref>
The inductions were first held in 2013: [[Manuel Alejandro]], [[José Ángel Espinoza]], [[José Feliciano]], [[Julio Iglesias]], [[Armando Manzanero]], [[Concha Valdés Miranda]], and [[Roberto Cantoral]] were the first songwriters to be inducted. The latter was posthumously inducted.<ref name="billboard"/> Mexico is the country with the most songwriters inducted with twelve.
